JOHANNESBURG - As South Africans enjoy the relaxation of lockdown regulations, the Health Department has dismissed reports of a potential resurgence of COVID-19 cases involving the Delta variant of the coronavirus. The Health Department gave an update on its response to the COVID-19 pandemic on Friday. Deputy Director General of the Health Department Dr Nicholas Crisp addressed claims that Delta - the deadliest COVID variant known so far - is on the rise within our borders. Crisp said there were no variants of concern, including Omicron, adding the country's vaccines were effective against this variant. LATEST FIGURES Saturday marks exactly two years since President Cyril Ramaphosa announced South Africa's first lockdown in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. In 2020, restrictions were expected to last for 21 days which then turned into weeks and then months and then years with the country now under 730 days of lockdown, 1,560 new cases have been recorded in the last 24 hours with one death being reported, bringing the known death toll to 99,939. As of today the cumulative number of #COVID19 cases identified in SA is 3 709 209 with 2 120 new cases reported. Today 07 deaths have been reported bringing the total to 99 939 deaths. The cumulative number of recoveries now stand at 3 595 512 with a recovery rate of 96.9% pic.twitter.com/X9z9UZOGx8 